a-octo-dimensions=\"link_type:self\" href=\"https://github.com/langmore\">@langmore</a> <a class=\"user-mention\" data-hovercard-type=\"user\" data-hovercard-url=\"/hovercards?user_id=1794715\" data-octo-click=\"hovercard-link-click\" data-octo-dimensions=\"link_type:self\" href=\"https://github.com/ebrevdo\">@ebrevdo</a>,</p>\n<p>I'm interested in performing differentiable matrix solves with TensorFlow using Krylov subspace methods (for sparse or structured matrices). I was considering making a conjugate gradient solver, since that's what I need at the moment, and was wondering if that would be worthy of contributing somewhere? Or if it's already been done? I was planning to use <code>tf.while_loop</code> and <code>tf.linalg.LinearOperator</code>, and to implement the gradient using the standard $dA^{-1}/dx = -A^{-1} dA/dx A^{-1}$ formula.</p>\n<p>Any advice/pointers would be appreciated. Thanks!</p>", "body_text": "Hi @langmore @ebrevdo,\nI'm interested in performing differentiable matrix solves with TensorFlow using Krylov subspace methods (for sparse or structured matrices). I was considering making a conjugate gradient solver, since that's what I need at the moment, and was wondering if that would be worthy of contributing somewhere? Or if it's already been done? I was planning to use tf.while_loop and tf.linalg.LinearOperator, and to implement the gradient using the standard $dA^{-1}/dx = -A^{-1} dA/dx A^{-1}$ formula.\nAny advice/pointers would be appreciated. Thanks!", "body": "Hi @langmore @ebrevdo,\r\n\r\nI'm interested in performing differentiable matrix solves with TensorFlow using Krylov subspace methods (for sparse or structured matrices). I was considering making a conjugate gradient solver, since that's what I need at the moment, and was wondering if that would be worthy of contributing somewhere? Or if it's already been done? I was planning to use `tf.while_loop` and `tf.linalg.LinearOperator`, and to implement the gradient using the standard $dA^{-1}/dx = -A^{-1} dA/dx A^{-1}$ formula.\r\n\r\nAny advice/pointers would be appreciated. Thanks!"}